[{"content":"\u003cp\u003e\u003cimg src=\"/projects/Specialization/Specialization-thumb.jpg\" alt=\"Cover Image\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch1 id=\"introduction\"\u003eIntroduction\u003c/h1\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eFor my specialization project at The Game Assembly I set out to create a real time SDF renderer. A \u003ca href=\"https://www.codrea.nu\"\u003efriend\u003c/a\u003e of mine showed me a video of someone making an entire game engine using only signed distance functions (SDF), which caught my interest and made me want to try it out. It\u0026rsquo;s uncommon in in games due to both its performance cost but also because of how different it is to create assets for than traditional mesh rendering. My main goal was mostly to try it out and attempt to make an SDF renderer as optimized as I possibly could in the time allocated for the project.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch1 id=\"what-is-sdf\"\u003eWhat is SDF?\u003c/h1\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eA signed distance function is a mathematical function that takes a point as input and returns the distance to a shape\u0026rsquo;s surface. The \u0026ldquo;signed\u0026rdquo; part means the distance is negative if the point is inside the shape and positive if it\u0026rsquo;s outside. Below is an example of what a sphere\u0026rsquo;s SDF would look like in HLSL:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cdiv class=\"highlight\"\u003e\u003cpre tabindex=\"0\" style=\"color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;-webkit-text-size-adjust:none;\"\u003e\u003ccode class=\"language-HLSL\" data-lang=\"HLSL\"\u003e\u003cspan style=\"display:flex;\"\u003e\u003cspan\u003e\u003cspan style=\"color:#66d9ef\"\u003efloat\u003c/span\u003e SphereSDF(\u003cspan style=\"color:#66d9ef\"\u003efloat3\u003c/span\u003e aPoint, \u003cspan style=\"color:#66d9ef\"\u003efloat\u003c/span\u003e aRadius)\n\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan style=\"display:flex;\"\u003e\u003cspan\u003e{\n\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan style=\"display:flex;\"\u003e\u003cspan\u003e  \u003cspan style=\"color:#66d9ef\"\u003ereturn\u003c/span\u003e length(aPoint) \u003cspan style=\"color:#f92672\"\u003e-\u003c/span\u003e aRadius;\n\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan style=\"display:flex;\"\u003e\u003cspan\u003e}\n\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003cp\u003eThese distances are then used for rendering by using raymarching. Raymarching works by finding the distance of the closest surface and then marching along the ray that distance to then sample the scene again. This is done iteratively until the distance falls within a threshold to be counted as a hit. Below is an interactive demo showing this process in action:\n\u003cdiv id=\"sdf-demo-wrap\" style=\"width:100%;margin:1.5rem 0;\"\u003e\r\n  \u003ccanvas id=\"sdf-canvas\" style=\"display:block;width:100%;border-radius:4px;cursor:crosshair;\"\u003e\u003c/canvas\u003e\r\n\u003c/div\u003e\r\n\r\n\u003cscript\u003e\r\n(function() {\r\n  const canvas = document.getElementById('sdf-canvas');\r\n  const ctx    = canvas.getContext('2d');\r\n\r\n  function getColors() {\r\n    const bodyStyle = getComputedStyle(document.body);\r\n    const codeEl    = document.querySelector('pre code, .highlight pre, pre, code');\r\n    const codeStyle = codeEl ? getComputedStyle(codeEl) : null;\r\n    return {\r\n      bg:      codeStyle ? codeStyle.backgroundColor : bodyStyle.backgroundColor,\r\n      primary: codeStyle ? codeStyle.color           : bodyStyle.color,\r\n      text:    bodyStyle.color,\r\n    };\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  function toRGB(cssColor) {\r\n    const tmp = document.createElement('canvas');\r\n    tmp.width = tmp.height = 1;\r\n    const c = tmp.getContext('2d');\r\n    c.fillStyle = cssColor;\r\n    c.fillRect(0, 0, 1, 1);\r\n    const d = c.getImageData(0, 0, 1, 1).data;\r\n    return `${d[0]},${d[1]},${d[2]}`;\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  function resize() {\r\n    const w = canvas.parentElement.clientWidth;\r\n    canvas.width  = w;\r\n    canvas.height = Math.round(w * 0.62);\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  function getObstacles() {\r\n    const W = canvas.width, H = canvas.height;\r\n    return [\r\n      { x: W*0.22, y: H*0.22, r: W*0.09 },\r\n      { x: W*0.72, y: H*0.20, r: W*0.11 },\r\n      { x: W*0.58, y: H*0.72, r: W*0.13 },\r\n      { x: W*0.26, y: H*0.80, r: W*0.10 },\r\n      { x: W*0.83, y: H*0.60, r: W*0.09 },\r\n    ];\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  function sceneSDF(px, py, obs) {\r\n    let d = Infinity;\r\n    for (const o of obs) {\r\n      const dd = Math.hypot(px - o.x, py - o.y) - o.r;\r\n      if (dd \u003c d) d = dd;\r\n    }\r\n    return d;\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  let mouseX = null, mouseY = null;\r\n\r\n  canvas.addEventListener('mousemove', e =\u003e {\r\n    const r = canvas.getBoundingClientRect();\r\n    mouseX = (e.clientX - r.left) * (canvas.width  / r.width);\r\n    mouseY = (e.clientY - r.top)  * (canvas.height / r.height);\r\n    draw();\r\n  });\r\n  canvas.addEventListener('mouseleave', () =\u003e { mouseX = null; mouseY = null; draw(); });\r\n  canvas.addEventListener('touchmove', e =\u003e {\r\n    e.preventDefault();\r\n    const r = canvas.getBoundingClientRect();\r\n    mouseX = (e.touches[0].clientX - r.left) * (canvas.width  / r.width);\r\n    mouseY = (e.touches[0].clientY - r.top)  * (canvas.height / r.height);\r\n    draw();\r\n  }, { passive: false });\r\n\r\n  function draw() {\r\n    const W = canvas.width, H = canvas.height;\r\n    const colors = getColors();\r\n    const pRGB   = toRGB(colors.primary);\r\n    const bgRGB  = toRGB(colors.bg);\r\n\r\n    const ox = W * 0.06, oy = H * 0.50;\r\n    const tx = mouseX != null ? mouseX : W * 0.72;\r\n    const ty = mouseY != null ? mouseY : oy;\r\n    let dx = tx - ox, dy = ty - oy;\r\n    const len = Math.hypot(dx, dy);\r\n    if (len \u003c 1) return;\r\n    dx /= len; dy /= len;\r\n\r\n    ctx.fillStyle = colors.bg;\r\n    ctx.fillRect(0, 0, W, H);\r\n\r\n    ctx.strokeStyle = `rgba(${pRGB},0.07)`;\r\n    ctx.lineWidth = 1;\r\n    const step = W / 14;\r\n    for (let x = 0; x \u003c= W; x += step) { ctx.beginPath(); ctx.moveTo(x,0); ctx.lineTo(x,H); ctx.stroke(); }\r\n    for (let y = 0; y \u003c= H; y += step) { ctx.beginPath(); ctx.moveTo(0,y); ctx.lineTo(W,y); ctx.stroke(); }\r\n\r\n    const obs = getObstacles();\r\n    for (const o of obs) {\r\n      ctx.beginPath();\r\n      ctx.arc(o.x, o.y, o.r, 0, Math.PI*2);\r\n      ctx.fillStyle = `rgba(${bgRGB},0.6)`;\r\n      ctx.fill();\r\n      ctx.strokeStyle = `rgba(${pRGB},0.45)`;\r\n      ctx.lineWidth = 1.5;\r\n      ctx.stroke();\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    const steps = [];\r\n    let t = 0, hit = false;\r\n    for (let i = 0; i \u003c 64; i++) {\r\n      const px = ox + dx*t, py = oy + dy*t;\r\n      const d = sceneSDF(px, py, obs);\r\n      steps.push({ px, py, d });\r\n      if (d \u003c= 2.5) { hit = true; break; }\r\n      if (px \u003c 0 || px \u003e W || py \u003c 0 || py \u003e H) { break; }\r\n      if (t + d \u003e W*50.0) { t += d; break; }\r\n      t += d;\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    for (let i = steps.length-1; i \u003e= 0; i--) {\r\n      const s = steps[i], a = 0.10 + 0.08*(i/steps.length);\r\n      ctx.beginPath(); ctx.arc(s.px, s.py, s.d, 0, Math.PI*2);\r\n      ctx.strokeStyle = `rgba(${pRGB},${a+0.12})`; ctx.lineWidth = 1.2; ctx.stroke();\r\n      ctx.fillStyle   = `rgba(${pRGB},${a*0.25})`; ctx.fill();\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    const last = steps[steps.length-1];\r\n    const endX = last.px, endY = last.py;\r\n    const rRGB = hit ? '255,90,80' : pRGB;\r\n\r\n    ctx.beginPath(); ctx.moveTo(ox,oy); ctx.lineTo(endX,endY);\r\n    ctx.strokeStyle = `rgba(${pRGB},0.10)`; ctx.lineWidth = 7; ctx.stroke();\r\n    ctx.beginPath(); ctx.moveTo(ox,oy); ctx.lineTo(endX,endY);\r\n    ctx.strokeStyle = `rgba(${rRGB},0.85)`; ctx.lineWidth = 1.5; ctx.setLineDash([]); ctx.stroke();\r\n\r\n    if (!hit) {\r\n      ctx.beginPath(); ctx.moveTo(endX,endY); ctx.lineTo(ox+dx*W*1.5, oy+dy*W*1.5);\r\n      ctx.strokeStyle = `rgba(${pRGB},0.15)`; ctx.setLineDash([4,6]); ctx.lineWidth=1; ctx.stroke();\r\n      ctx.setLineDash([]);\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    for (let i = 0; i \u003c steps.length; i++) {\r\n      const s = steps[i], isHit = i===steps.length-1 \u0026\u0026 hit;\r\n      ctx.beginPath(); ctx.arc(s.px, s.py, isHit?4:3, 0, Math.PI*2);\r\n      ctx.fillStyle = isHit ? 'rgba(255,90,80,0.95)' : `rgba(${pRGB},0.9)`; ctx.fill();\r\n    }\r\n\r\n    ctx.beginPath(); ctx.arc(ox,oy,5,0,Math.PI*2);\r\n    ctx.fillStyle = colors.text; ctx.fill();\r\n    ctx.beginPath(); ctx.arc(ox,oy,9,0,Math.PI*2);\r\n    ctx.strokeStyle = `rgba(${pRGB},0.3)`; ctx.lineWidth=1.5; ctx.stroke();\r\n\r\n    ctx.font = `${Math.round(W*0.018)}px \"Fira Code\", monospace`;\r\n    ctx.fillStyle = `rgba(${pRGB},0.55)`;\r\n    ctx.fillText('origin', ox+12, oy-10);\r\n    ctx.fillStyle = hit ? 'rgba(255,100,80,0.8)' : `rgba(${pRGB},0.6)`;\r\n    ctx.fillText(`${steps.length} iterations · ${hit?'HIT':'miss'}`, W*0.04, H*0.96);\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  \r\n  resize();\r\n  requestAnimationFrame(() =\u003e { requestAnimationFrame(() =\u003e draw()); });\r\n  window.addEventListener('resize', () =\u003e { resize(); draw(); });\r\n  new MutationObserver(() =\u003e draw())\r\n    .observe(document.body, { attributeFilter: ['class'] });\r\n})();\r\n\u003c/script\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch1 id=\"project-setup\"\u003eProject Setup\u003c/h1\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAs an engine I decided to use my project from our old graphics course. I decided to do this mostly to minimize bloat as I knew most logic would happen in a shader and I would still need to make my own rendering pipeline. The first few days of the project was mostly spent ripping out old mesh based code and replacing the pipeline with just a fullscreen quad output from a vertex shader going into a pixel shader doing all the raymarching.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch1 id=\"performance\"\u003ePerformance\u003c/h1\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eI knew before even starting that performance would be a big issue since for every ray\u0026rsquo;s scene sample many complex math functions would be calculated each frame. One major optimization I implemented was to use a 3D texture as a brickmap to cache previously calculated values to be able to sample the brickmap instead of recalculating all SDFs. To be able to increase the render distance without consuming too much memory I used multiple brickmaps stacked on top of each other with increasing size but decreasing resolution acting as LOD for objects farther away.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cdiv style=\"text-align: left;\"\u003e\r\n  \u003cvideo width=\"50%\" autoplay muted loop\u003e\r\n    \u003csource src=\"/videos/brickmap.mp4\" type=\"video/mp4\"\u003e\r\n  \u003c/video\u003e\r\n\u003c/div\u003e\r\n\u003ch6 id=\"brickmap-cells-colored-and-size-exaggerated-for-demonstration\"\u003e(Brickmap cells colored and size exaggerated for demonstration)\u003c/h6\u003e\n\u003ch1 id=\"sdf-operations\"\u003eSDF operations\u003c/h1\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eOne of the things that really interested me with SDF is the flexibility you can do with SDF operations due to SDF being purely mathematical functions. SDF operations work as sort of filters to the calculations and can be used to create unique effects that wouldn\u0026rsquo;t really be viable when using traditional rendering methods due to the performance cost of rebuilding meshes. The three operations I decided to implement were unions, subtractions and intersections.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch4 id=\"union\"\u003eUnion\u003c/h4\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eA union is defined by the minimum distance of two shapes resulting in them combining into one. This is the most common operation as the entire scene could be viewed as one big union.\n\u003cfigure\u003e\u003cimg src=\"/images/union.png\" width=\"30%\"\u003e\n\u003c/figure\u003e\n\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch6 id=\"minab\"\u003emin(a,b)\u003c/h6\u003e\n\u003ch4 id=\"subtraction\"\u003eSubtraction\u003c/h4\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eSubtraction can be used to remove volumes from shapes. It can be thought of as creating a hole in the shape of one SDF in another.\n\u003cfigure\u003e\u003cimg src=\"/images/subtraction.png\" width=\"30%\"\u003e\n\u003c/figure\u003e\n\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch6 id=\"max-ab\"\u003emax(-a,b)\u003c/h6\u003e\n\u003ch4 id=\"intersection\"\u003eIntersection\u003c/h4\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAn intersection only shows the part where two shapes intersect. This is something I implemented but ended up not using as most things didn\u0026rsquo;t intersect so it made most of the scene invisible.\n\u003cfigure\u003e\u003cimg src=\"/images/intersection.png\" width=\"30%\"\u003e\n\u003c/figure\u003e\n\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003ch6 id=\"maxab\"\u003emax(a,b)\u003c/h6\u003e\n\u003cdiv id=\"sdf-ops-wrap\" style=\"width:100%;margin:1.5rem 0;\"\u003e\r\n  \u003ccanvas id=\"sdf-ops-canvas\" style=\"display:block;width:100%;border-radius:4px;cursor:grab;\"\u003e\u003c/canvas\u003e\r\n  \u003cdiv id=\"sdf-ops-btns\" style=\"display:flex;gap:8px;margin-top:8px;flex-wrap:wrap;\"\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\r\n\u003c/div\u003e\r\n\r\n\u003cscript\u003e\r\n(function() {\r\n  const canvas = document.getElementById('sdf-ops-canvas');\r\n  const ctx    = canvas.getContext('2d');\r\n  const btnsEl = document.getElementById('sdf-ops-btns');\r\n\r\n  \r\n  function getColors() {\r\n    const bodyStyle = getComputedStyle(document.body);\r\n    const codeEl    = document.querySelector('pre code, .highlight pre, pre, code');\r\n    const codeStyle = codeEl ? getComputedStyle(codeEl) : null;\r\n    return {\r\n      bg:      codeStyle ? codeStyle.backgroundColor : bodyStyle.backgroundColor,\r\n      primary: codeStyle ? codeStyle.color           : bodyStyle.color,\r\n      text:    bodyStyle.color,\r\n    };\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  function toRGB(cssColor) {\r\n    const tmp = document.createElement('canvas');\r\n    tmp.width = tmp.height = 1;\r\n    const c = tmp.getContext('2d');\r\n    c.fillStyle = cssColor;\r\n    c.fillRect(0, 0, 1, 1);\r\n    const d = c.getImageData(0, 0, 1, 1).data;\r\n    return [d[0], d[1], d[2]];\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  \r\n  const OPS = [\r\n    { id: 'union',     label: 'Union',     fn: (a, b) =\u003e Math.min(a, b) },\r\n    { id: 'subtract',  label: 'Subtract',  fn: (a, b) =\u003e Math.max(a, -b) },\r\n    { id: 'intersect', label: 'Intersect', fn: (a, b) =\u003e Math.max(a, b) },\r\n  ];\r\n  let activeOp = 0;\r\n\r\n  \r\n  function circleSDF(px, py, cx, cy, r) {\r\n    return Math.hypot(px - cx, py - cy) - r;\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  \r\n  let shapes, drag, dragOffX, dragOffY;\r\n\r\n  function initShapes() {\r\n    const W = canvas.width, H = canvas.height;\r\n    shapes = [\r\n      { x: W * 0.38, y: H * 0.5, r: W * 0.15 },\r\n      { x: W * 0.62, y: H * 0.5, r: W * 0.13 },\r\n    ];\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  \r\n  function resize() {\r\n    const w = canvas.parentElement.clientWidth;\r\n    const wasEmpty = !shapes;\r\n    canvas.width  = w;\r\n    canvas.height = Math.round(w * 0.56);\r\n    if (wasEmpty) initShapes();\r\n    else {\r\n      \r\n      shapes[0].x = canvas.width  * 0.38;\r\n      shapes[0].y = canvas.height * 0.5;\r\n      shapes[0].r = canvas.width  * 0.15;\r\n      shapes[1].x = canvas.width  * 0.62;\r\n      shapes[1].y = canvas.height * 0.5;\r\n      shapes[1].r = canvas.width  * 0.13;\r\n    }\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  \r\n  function draw() {\r\n    const W = canvas.width, H = canvas.height;\r\n    const colors = getColors();\r\n    const [pr, pg, pb] = toRGB(colors.primary);\r\n    const [br, bg_, bb] = toRGB(colors.bg);\r\n    const op = OPS[activeOp];\r\n    const k  = canvas.width * 0.06; \r\n\r\n    \r\n    ctx.fillStyle = colors.bg;\r\n    ctx.fillRect(0, 0, W, H);\r\n\r\n    \r\n    ctx.strokeStyle = `rgba(${pr},${pg},${pb},0.06)`;\r\n    ctx.lineWidth = 1;\r\n    const step = W / 14;\r\n    for (let x = 0; x \u003c= W; x += step) { ctx.beginPath(); ctx.moveTo(x,0); ctx.lineTo(x,H); ctx.stroke(); }\r\n    for (let y = 0; y \u003c= H; y += step) { ctx.beginPath(); ctx.moveTo(0,y); ctx.lineTo(W,y); ctx.stroke(); }\r\n\r\n    const s0 = shapes[0], s1 = shapes[1];\r\n\r\n    \r\n    const stride = 3;\r\n    const imgData = ctx.getImageData(0, 0, W, H);\r\n    const data    = imgData.data;\r\n\r\n    for (let py = 0; py \u003c H; py += stride) {\r\n      for (let px = 0; px \u003c W; px += stride) {\r\n        const dA = circleSDF(px, py, s0.x, s0.y, s0.r);\r\n        const dB = circleSDF(px, py, s1.x, s1.y, s1.r);\r\n        const d  = activeOp === 3\r\n          ? op.fn(dA, dB, k)\r\n          : op.fn(dA, dB);\r\n\r\n        if (d \u003c 0) {\r\n          \r\n          const alpha = Math.min(1, -d / 4) * 0.55;\r\n          const r_ = Math.round(br + (pr - br) * 0.35);\r\n          const g_ = Math.round(bg_ + (pg - bg_) * 0.35);\r\n          const b_ = Math.round(bb + (pb - bb) * 0.35);\r\n          for (let sy = 0; sy \u003c stride \u0026\u0026 py+sy \u003c H; sy++) {\r\n            for (let sx = 0; sx \u003c stride \u0026\u0026 px+sx \u003c W; sx++) {\r\n              const i = ((py+sy)*W + (px+sx)) * 4;\r\n              \r\n              data[i]   = Math.round(br   + (r_ - br)   * alpha);\r\n              data[i+1] = Math.round(bg_  + (g_ - bg_)  * alpha);\r\n              data[i+2] = Math.round(bb   + (b_ - bb)   * alpha);\r\n              data[i+3] = 255;\r\n            }\r\n          }\r\n        }\r\n      }\r\n    }\r\n    ctx.putImageData(imgData, 0, 0);\r\n\r\n    \r\n    [s0, s1].forEach((s, i) =\u003e {\r\n      ctx.beginPath();\r\n      ctx.arc(s.x, s.y, s.r, 0, Math.PI*2);\r\n      ctx.strokeStyle = `rgba(${pr},${pg},${pb},0.3)`;\r\n      ctx.setLineDash([5, 5]);\r\n      ctx.lineWidth = 1.2;\r\n      ctx.stroke();\r\n      ctx.setLineDash([]);\r\n\r\n      \r\n      ctx.beginPath();\r\n      ctx.arc(s.x, s.y, 4, 0, Math.PI*2);\r\n      ctx.fillStyle = `rgba(${pr},${pg},${pb},0.7)`;\r\n      ctx.fill();\r\n\r\n      \r\n      ctx.font = `${Math.round(W*0.018)}px \"Fira Code\", monospace`;\r\n      ctx.fillStyle = `rgba(${pr},${pg},${pb},0.5)`;\r\n      ctx.fillText(i === 0 ? 'A' : 'B', s.x + 8, s.y - 8);\r\n    });\r\n\r\n    \r\n    \r\n    const outlineData = ctx.getImageData(0, 0, W, H);\r\n    const od = outlineData.data;\r\n    const edgeW = 1.5;\r\n    for (let py = 0; py \u003c H; py++) {\r\n      for (let px = 0; px \u003c W; px++) {\r\n        const dA = circleSDF(px, py, s0.x, s0.y, s0.r);\r\n        const dB = circleSDF(px, py, s1.x, s1.y, s1.r);\r\n        const d  = activeOp === 3 ? op.fn(dA, dB, k) : op.fn(dA, dB);\r\n        if (Math.abs(d) \u003c edgeW) {\r\n          const t = 1 - Math.abs(d) / edgeW;\r\n          const i = (py * W + px) * 4;\r\n          od[i]   = Math.round(od[i]   + (pr - od[i])   * t * 0.9);\r\n          od[i+1] = Math.round(od[i+1] + (pg - od[i+1]) * t * 0.9);\r\n          od[i+2] = Math.round(od[i+2] + (pb - od[i+2]) * t * 0.9);\r\n          od[i+3] = 255;\r\n        }\r\n      }\r\n    }\r\n    ctx.putImageData(outlineData, 0, 0);\r\n\r\n    \r\n    ctx.font = `${Math.round(W*0.02)}px \"Fira Code\", monospace`;\r\n    ctx.fillStyle = `rgba(${pr},${pg},${pb},0.6)`;\r\n    ctx.fillText(op.label, W*0.04, H*0.96);\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  \r\n  function buildButtons() {\r\n    btnsEl.innerHTML = '';\r\n    const colors = getColors();\r\n    const [pr, pg, pb] = toRGB(colors.primary);\r\n\r\n    OPS.forEach((op, i) =\u003e {\r\n      const btn = document.createElement('button');\r\n      btn.textContent = op.label;\r\n      const isActive = i === activeOp;\r\n      btn.style.cssText = `\r\n        font-family: monospace;\r\n        font-size: 12px;\r\n        padding: 4px 12px;\r\n        background: ${isActive ? `rgba(${pr},${pg},${pb},0.15)` : 'transparent'};\r\n        border: 1px solid rgba(${pr},${pg},${pb},${isActive ? 0.7 : 0.25});\r\n        color: rgba(${pr},${pg},${pb},${isActive ? 1 : 0.5});\r\n        border-radius: 2px;\r\n        cursor: pointer;\r\n        letter-spacing: 0.05em;\r\n        transition: all 0.15s;\r\n      `;\r\n      btn.addEventListener('click', () =\u003e { activeOp = i; buildButtons(); draw(); });\r\n      btnsEl.appendChild(btn);\r\n    });\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  \r\n  function getPos(e) {\r\n    const r = canvas.getBoundingClientRect();\r\n    const scaleX = canvas.width  / r.width;\r\n    const scaleY = canvas.height / r.height;\r\n    const clientX = e.touches ? e.touches[0].clientX : e.clientX;\r\n    const clientY = e.touches ? e.touches[0].clientY : e.clientY;\r\n    return [(clientX - r.left) * scaleX, (clientY - r.top) * scaleY];\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  function onDown(e) {\r\n    const [mx, my] = getPos(e);\r\n    for (let i = 0; i \u003c shapes.length; i++) {\r\n      const s = shapes[i];\r\n      if (Math.hypot(mx - s.x, my - s.y) \u003c s.r) {\r\n        drag = i;\r\n        dragOffX = mx - s.x;\r\n        dragOffY = my - s.y;\r\n        canvas.style.cursor = 'grabbing';\r\n        break;\r\n      }\r\n    }\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  function onMove(e) {\r\n    if (drag == null) return;\r\n    e.preventDefault();\r\n    const [mx, my] = getPos(e);\r\n    shapes[drag].x = mx - dragOffX;\r\n    shapes[drag].y = my - dragOffY;\r\n    draw();\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  function onUp() {\r\n    drag = null;\r\n    canvas.style.cursor = 'grab';\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  canvas.addEventListener('mousedown',  onDown);\r\n  canvas.addEventListener('mousemove',  onMove);\r\n  canvas.addEventListener('mouseup',    onUp);\r\n  canvas.addEventListener('mouseleave', onUp);\r\n  canvas.addEventListener('touchstart', e =\u003e { e.preventDefault(); onDown(e); }, { passive: false });\r\n  canvas.addEventListener('touchmove',  e =\u003e { e.preventDefault(); onMove(e); }, { passive: false });\r\n  canvas.addEventListener('touchend',   onUp);\r\n\r\n  \r\n  buildButtons();\r\n  resize();\r\n  requestAnimationFrame(() =\u003e { requestAnimationFrame(() =\u003e draw()); });\r\n  window.addEventListener('resize', () =\u003e { resize(); draw(); });\r\n  new MutationObserver(() =\u003e draw())\r\n    .observe(document.body, { attributeFilter: ['class'] });\r\n})();\r\n\u003c/script\u003e\r\n\n\u003ch6 id=\"drag-shapes-to-reposition\"\u003e(Drag shapes to reposition)\u003c/h6\u003e\n\u003ch1 id=\"geometry-rebuilding\"\u003eGeometry Rebuilding\u003c/h1\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eOne big advantage with SDF rendering is the low cost of geometry rebuilding you get in exchange for the cost of rendering. A popular effect is to use a smooth min instead of a normal min function when doing the different SDF operations. This is a very cheap effect that creates a sort of \u0026ldquo;blobby\u0026rdquo; look to the scene and was the first thing I decided to implement. Since the output of SDFs is just a single float that can be transformed however needed to achieve an effect. Below are some examples of simple effects you can apply to either individual objects or an entire scene.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cdiv style=\"display: flex; justify-content: center; gap: 16px; flex-wrap: wrap;\"\u003e\r\n  \u003cdiv style=\"text-align: center; width: 45%;\"\u003e\r\n    \u003cvideo style=\"width: 100%; aspect-ratio: 16/9;\" autoplay muted loop\u003e\r\n      \u003csource src=\"/videos/sdf-smoothing.mp4\" type=\"video/mp4\"\u003e\r\n    \u003c/video\u003e\r\n    \u003ch6\u003eSmoothing\u003c/h6\u003e\r\n  \u003c/div\u003e\r\n  \u003cdiv style=\"text-align: center; width: 45%;\"\u003e\r\n    \u003cvideo style=\"width: 100%; aspect-ratio: 16/9;\" autoplay muted loop\u003e\r\n      \u003csource src=\"/videos/sdf-ripple.mp4\" type=\"video/mp4\"\u003e\r\n    \u003c/video\u003e\r\n    \u003ch6\u003eRipple Effect + Smoothing\u003c/h6\u003e\r\n  \u003c/div\u003e\r\n\u003c/div\u003e\r\n\u003cdiv style=\"display: flex; justify-content: center; gap: 16px; flex-wrap: wrap;\"\u003e\r\n  \u003cdiv style=\"text-align: center; width: 45%;\"\u003e\r\n    \u003cvideo style=\"width: 100%; aspect-ratio: 16/9;\" autoplay muted loop\u003e\r\n      \u003csource src=\"/videos/sdf-repeat.mp4\" type=\"video/mp4\"\u003e\r\n    \u003c/video\u003e\r\n    \u003ch6\u003eWrapping the sample point\u003c/h6\u003e\r\n  \u003c/div\u003e\r\n  \u003cdiv style=\"text-align: center; width: 45%;\"\u003e\r\n    \u003cvideo style=\"width: 100%; aspect-ratio: 16/9;\" autoplay muted loop\u003e\r\n      \u003csource src=\"/videos/sdf-bending.mp4\" type=\"video/mp4\"\u003e\r\n    \u003c/video\u003e\r\n    \u003ch6\u003eBending the sample point\u003c/h6\u003e\r\n  \u003c/div\u003e\r\n\u003c/div\u003e\r\n\u003ch1 id=\"results\"\u003eResults\u003c/h1\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThere are some things I would have liked to improve if I had more time. I would have really liked to get rid of some strange artifacts that appear sometimes. I am pretty satisfied with the optimizations but I would have liked it to be even better as now it runs at about 50 FPS with 50 shapes. I considered implementing quad trees to optimize distance checking but I don\u0026rsquo;t think I would have had time. It would also have been nice if there was some sort of hierarchy/editor or something similar to be able to place and manipulate shapes in a more visual way. In general I\u0026rsquo;m very satisfied with the project and I think it was very fun to work on as well as a great learning experience!\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cdiv style=\"text-align: center;\"\u003e\r\n  \u003cvideo width=\"70%\" autoplay muted loop\u003e\r\n    \u003csource src=\"/videos/sdf-lump-boomerang-fast.mp4\" type=\"video/mp4\"\u003e\r\n  \u003c/video\u003e\r\n\u003c/div\u003e","description":null,"image":"images/thumbs/Specialization-thumb.jpg","permalink":"https://elias.fish/projects/specialization/","title":"SDF Renderer"},{"content":"\u003cp\u003ehej jag heter elias hej jag heter elias hej jag heter elias hej jag heter elias hej jag heter elias hej jag heter elias hej jag heter elias hej jag heter elias hej jag heter elias hej jag heter elias hej jag heter elias hej jag heter elias hej jag heter elias hej jag heter elias hej jag heter elias hej jag heter elias hej jag heter elias hej jag heter elias hej jag heter elias hej jag heter elias hej jag heter elias hej jag heter 